Defendant Andrew T Jordan in court with attorney Frederick F Klimetz.  Sara Nicole Volden Schroeder appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  
Deputy court clerk ccp.
Case set for sentencing hearing. Parties are prepared to proceed. State placed negotiations on the record. State requested to orally amend the Information to refelct the correct offense location. Defense does not object. Court granted the State's request. Court found the State complied with the victim rights legislation. Statements made as to sentencing. Additional statements made by Roosevelt M., Lawrence P. 

As to COUNT 1-
The Court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM TERM OF IMPRISONMENT of 36 MONTHS, with credit for 11 days time served; the INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin State Prison System is 18 MONTHS; the MAXIMUM TERM OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION is 18 MONTHS.  

Defendant is eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program. The defendant is eligible for the Substance Abuse Program.

Court STAYED the sentence and placed defendant on probation for 30 MONTHS with the following conditions:
1) Court ordered the defendant to serve 90 DAYS condition time in the House of Correction, FORTHWITH; Defendant may have release for employment if currently employed, release for school if currently enrolled. Defendant pay participate in job training;
2) Maintain absolute sobriety from all illegal drugs and alcohol;
3) Provide any prescriptions to agent before filling them;
4) Pay all costs, fees, surcharges, and fines during period of probation. Court will allow the defendant to enter into a payment plan. Failure to pay will result in a civil judgment;
5) Defendant's driver's license is revoked for a period of 2 YEARS;
6) Provide DNA sample and pay DNA surcharge;
7) Pay a fine of $300.00;
8) Obtain GED/HSED;
9) Maintain employment of at least 30 hours per week;
10) No driving without a valid driver's license;
11) Court set restitution at ZERO;

If revoked, court costs, fees, surcharges and fines be paid through collection by the department of Corrections from 25% of funds. 

Appellate rights notice given to the defendant. 
